<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-201-320 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 440 563</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  March 12 1991 v5 n10 p81(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Macweek 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sales up, but Mass Micro posts '90 loss. (Mass Microsystems Inc.'sfinances, fiscal year 1990)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Norr, Henry.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Mass Micro Systems Inc. (Finance).andO;Ticker:    MMIC.andO;Topic:     Financial AnalysisLossesStorage MediaProfitBusiness PlanningSalesMultimedia TechnologyHardware VendorsFourth QuarterMarketing Strategy.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Henry NorrandM;Sunnyvale, Calif.andP;  -- Despite an increase in sales, Mass Microsystems Inc.andO;last month posted a loss for fiscal 1990, ended Dec.andP;  31.andM;The company, which markets Mac video and storage systems, recorded a net lossof $250,000, or 5 cents per share, for the year, compared with net income of$965,000, or 26 cents per share, for fiscal 1989.andP;  Revenues for 1990 were$21.32 million, up 10 percent from the year before.andM;The fiscal-year results reflected a $712,000 loss in the fourth quarter onsales of $4.98 million, down from $5.4 million for the same period a yearago.andP;  The company issued a warning in late November that it faced strongprice and margin pressures on its SyQuest removable-cartridge hard drives andthat the recession was slowing multimedia product sales.andM;Carl Pompei, chairman and co-CEO of 4-year-old Mass Micro, said the companycould face another difficult quarter, but predicted that it will return toprofitability by midyear.andP;  &quot;We're cutting costs, and the business is alreadytrending in the right direction.andP;  We're pretty well positioned to takeadvantage of Apple's rising sales,&quot; he said.andM;The December 1990 acquisition of multimedia developer HyperPro Inc., lastmonth's announcement of the DataPak 88 line of high-capacityremovable-cartridge drives and the scheduled introduction by midyear ofseveral new video products are keys to Mass Micro's recovery plans, Pompeisaid.andM;In multimedia, Pompei said, the company is focusing on niche markets,including sales to specialized value-added resellers.andM;Mass Micro's shares closed March 6 at $1.48, far below their 52-week high of$8.63, but up from a low of 43 cents earlier this year.andO;</TEXT></DOC>